# ============================================================
# HFWastelandZ — Town Definitions
# File: HFTowns_<MapBasename>.conf  (this example is for Arland)
# Location: $profile: directory
#
# WHAT THIS IS
# Towns are the foundation of the spawn system. Each town is a
# named center point + radius + type. Towns drive every other
# spawn subsystem: loot crate placement, vehicle spawning, map
# markers, town radar, mission anchors, HVT zones, etc.
#
# HOW THE GAME FINDS THIS FILE
# At server boot, HFTownConfig looks for these files in $profile:
#   1. HFTowns_<MapBasename>.conf   ← preferred (per-map)
#   2. HFTowns.conf                  ← generic fallback
# MapBasename comes from the loaded world filename (e.g. Arland).
#
# AUTO-POPULATING FROM A LOADED MAP
# Don't write this file by hand for a new map. Instead:
#   1. Set TOWN_EXTRACT_ON_BOOT 1 in HFWastelandZ_server.conf
#   2. Boot the server once with the new map loaded
#   3. The extractor writes HFTowns_<MapBasename>_generated.conf
#      with every named location it finds (city, town, village,
#      military base) from the engine map descriptor system.
#   4. Review the generated file, edit radii / types / names.
#   5. Rename to HFTowns_<MapBasename>.conf to activate.
#   6. Set TOWN_EXTRACT_ON_BOOT 0.
#
# CAPTURING POSITIONS MANUALLY
# Use HFCoordTool in the editor (admin keybind) to capture exact
# world positions of any spot, then edit the X / Y / Z fields below.
#
# ============================================================
# FORMAT
# ============================================================
#
#   TOWN <name> <radius> <type> <X> <Y> <Z> [radar_on] [circle_visible]
#
#   name    Town display name. NO SPACES — use underscores. Must be
#           unique across the file. Shown on the world map.
#   radius  Town radius in meters from the center point. Drives
#           which tier the town gets (small/medium/large) for
#           loot/vehicle slot counts. Recommended ranges:
#               small  : 150 - 300   (outposts, hamlets)
#               medium : 301 - 450   (towns, small bases)
#               large  : 451 - 800   (cities, military bases)
#           Above 800 is allowed but unusual.
#   type    Town category. Determines which loot pool the town
#           draws from (configured in HFLootPools_<map>.conf).
#           Valid values:
#               civilian   — towns, villages, residential
#               military   — bases, airfields, depots
#               industrial — factories, warehouses, ports
#               special    — bunkers, relics, lore-locked sites
#   X Y Z   World position. Y is normally 0; the spawn system
#           terrain-snaps when actually placing crates/vehicles.
#
#   radar_on       (OPTIONAL) 1 = radar active for this town (default).
#                  0 = this town never triggers radar (circle stays
#                  white even when players are inside). Use for safe
#                  zones or spawn areas you don't want to light up.
#   circle_visible (OPTIONAL) 1 = circle shown on map (default).
#                  0 = circle hidden. Town still functions for loot/
#                  vehicles/radar checks, just not drawn on the map.
#
# Lines starting with # or // are comments. Blank lines OK.
#
# ============================================================
# PER-TOWN VEHICLE OVERRIDE (OPTIONAL)
# ============================================================
# Append 'veh:N' to any TOWN row to override the tier default
# vehicle count for that specific town only. Default = tier value
# from HFTownTiers.conf.
#
# Examples:
#   TOWN Island_Outpost 150 civilian 3900 0 1200 1 1 veh:2
#     → this specific town spawns 2 vehicles (tier default would
#       be 4 for a small town).
#
#   TOWN Bunker_Echo 80 special 5100 0 3300 1 0 veh:0
#     → this town spawns NO vehicles at all (veh:0 is a first-
#       class option — respawn never fires, map stays clean).
#
# Towns without 'veh:N' continue to use the tier default. Order
# of optional fields doesn't matter: 'veh:N' can appear before or
# after the positional radar_on/circle_visible flags.
#
# Re-extraction note: if you regenerate the town list via
# TOWN_EXTRACT_ON_BOOT, your 'veh:N' overrides will be lost —
# the extractor only writes the positional fields. Keep a backup
# before re-extracting.
#
# ============================================================
# EXAMPLE TOWNS (placeholder coordinates — REPLACE THESE)
# ============================================================
#
# These are illustrative placeholders. They are NOT real Arland
# locations. To get real Arland data, use TOWN_EXTRACT_ON_BOOT
# (see above) — that will write a proper starter file with the
# actual map's named locations.
#
# Layout intent (for reference only):
#   - 1 large military base (top-tier loot, vehicles)
#   - 1 medium civilian town (mid-tier survival + civilian gear)
#   - 1 medium industrial site (mixed tools, fuel, parts)
#   - 1 small special bunker (rare, low slot count, top quality)
#   - 1 small civilian outpost (basic survival)
#

TOWN Outpost_North         300  military    3200  0  2800
TOWN Harbor_East           400  civilian    2400  0  1800
TOWN Industrial_Zone       350  industrial  2500  0  1900
TOWN Bunker_Site_Echo      250  special     5800  0  4200
TOWN Highway_Stop          200  civilian    1500  0  3500

# ============================================================
# RECOMMENDED COUNTS PER MAP SIZE
# ============================================================
#   Small map  ( <40km²) :  6 - 10 towns
#   Medium map (40-80km²): 10 - 16 towns
#   Large map  ( >80km²) : 16 - 24 towns
#
# More towns = more spread-out PvP, less concentration. Fewer
# towns = more loot density per location, more contested fights.
# ============================================================
